[1] China National update: 571 confirmed cases, 17 deaths, 25 provinces - National Health Committee
Date: Thu 23 Jan 2020
Source: National Health Committee [in Chinese, machine trans., edited]
http://www.nhc.gov.cn/yjb/s3578/202001/5d19a4f6d3154b9fae328918ed2e3c8a.shtml


Epidemic situation of new coronavirus infection on [23 Jan 2020]
-----------------------------
As of 24:00 on [22 Jan 2020], our committee had received a total of 571 confirmed cases of pneumonia of new coronavirus infection in 25 provinces (autonomous regions, municipalities) in China, including 95 severe cases and 17 deaths (all from Hubei Province). A total of 393 suspected cases were reported in 13 provinces (autonomous regions and municipalities).

At 00:00 on [22 Jan 2020] 24 provinces (autonomous regions and municipalities) reported 131 new confirmed cases and 8 new deaths, of which 5 were males and 3 were females, with the exception of 1 individual who was 53 years old, the remaining fatalities were elderly individual over age 65 years. Elderly individuals (and there were 5 cases over 80 years old) have chronic diseases such as cancer, liver damage, hypertension, coronary heart disease, diabetes, and Parkinson's disease. 13 provinces (autonomous regions and municipalities) reported 257 new suspected cases. A total of 25 provinces (autonomous regions and municipalities) reported epidemics nationwide, and 4 provinces including Hebei, Liaoning, Jiangsu, and Fujian were added.

Confirmed cases reported overseas: 1 case in Hong Kong, China, 1 case in Macau, 1 case in Taiwan, China; 1 case in the United States, 1 case in Japan, 3 cases in Thailand, and 1 case in South Korea.

At present, 5897 close contacts have been traced, 969 people have been released from medical observation, and 4928 people are still under medical observation.

Information on the 17 deaths
----------------------------
1. A 61-year-old male with a history of liver cirrhosis and myxoma. Fever started on [20 Dec 2019], with cough and weakness. [He] was hospitalized in the Department of Respiratory Medicine of Wuhan Puren Hospital on [27 Dec 2019], transferred to the ICU on [28 Dec 2019], had mechanical intubation on [30 Dec 2019], and transferred to the ICU of Jinyintan Hospital on [31 Dec 2019]; in shock and a coma when transferred. On [1 Jan 2020] he received ECMO [extracorporeal membrane oxygenation] support, anti-infection, anti-shock, and corrective acid symptomatic supportive treatment. At 20:47 on [9 Jan 2020], the heart rate of the patient suddenly became zero, and the ECMO blood flow rate decreased rapidly to 0.2 liters/minute. Resuscitation was performed immediately. By 23:13, the heart rate was still 0, and clinical death was announced.

2. A 69-year-old male, was admitted to Wuhan Red Cross Hospital for 2 days due to fever and cough for 4 days, and exacerbated by dyspnea. On [3 Jan 2020], tracheal intubation was connected to a ventilator to assist breathing. Abnormal myocardial enzyme profile persisted. Transferred to Jinyintan Hospital on [4 Jan 2020]. Admission diagnosis was acute respiratory distress syndrome, respiratory failure, severe pneumonia, unconsciousness, pleural effusion, and aortic atherosclerosis. A CT scan of the patient's chest revealed large ground-glass opacities in both lungs. ECG: ST-segment changes. After admission, he was treated with intensive care, ventilator-assisted breathing, prone ventilation, and symptomatic and supportive treatments such as CRRT, anti-infection, and liver protection. His condition did not improve. Septic shock, microcirculation failure, coagulation dysfunction developed. At 00:15 on [15 Jan 2020], the patient's heart rate dropped to 0, and norepinephrine, epinephrine, pituitary, and dopamine were continuously pumped into the anti-shock therapy. The patient failed to recover spontaneous breathing and heartbeat until 0:45. The electrocardiogram at the bedside showed total cardiac arrest, and clinical death was declared.

3. An 89-year-old male, with a history of hypertension, cerebral infarction, and cerebral softening. Due to urinary incontinence, he was referred to the Department of Urology, Tongji Hospital on [5 Jan 2020], and was transferred to the emergency department on [8 Jan 2020] due to drowsiness and unconsciousness. The examination revealed lung infection (viral pneumonia) and acute respiratory failure. On [8 Jan 2020], a physical examination revealed that the patient had [a systolic blood pressure of ] 77mmHg and hypoxia. Lung CT showed double lung patch shadow, bilateral pleural effusion, and pleural adhesion. Routine blood tests showed a progressive increase in white blood cell count and a low lymphocyte count. On [9 Jan 2020], he was transferred to the outpatient clinic for emergency treatment and was given symptomatic supportive treatment. On [13 Jan 2020], the ventilator was assisted with positive pressure ventilation. Drowsiness occurred on [14 Jan 2020]. With ventilator-assisted ventilation, blood oxygen saturation fluctuated between 50% and 85%. He was admitted to the Infectious Diseases Ward on [15 Jan 2020]. Before transfer at 10:30 on [18 Jan 2020], Bp140 / 78mmHg, SPO2 85% under non-invasive ventilator-assisted ventilation. During the transfer, the patient suffered a respiratory arrest, continued resuscitation for 2 hours, but the treatment was unsuccessful. Clinical death was announced at 13:37 on [18 Jan 2020].

4. An 89-year-old male, with prior history of hypertension, diabetes, coronary heart disease, frequent premature ventricular contractions, and coronary stent implantation. The patient developed symptoms on [13 Jan 2020]. There was no obvious onset of asthma 4 hours before the consultation, and he felt dyspnea and no fever. On [18 Jan 2020], he went to the emergency department of Wuhan Union Medical College for treatment due to severe breathing difficulties. The patient was old and had a positive specimen with _Chlamydia pneumoniae_, a new coronavirus positive test, and CT of the lung showed typical changes of viral pneumonia. At 23:39 on [19 Jan 2020], his condition deteriorated, and he died.

5. A 66-year-old male, prior history of COPD [chronic obstructive pulmonary disease], hypertension, type 2 diabetes, chronic renal insufficiency, ascending aortic artificial aorta replacement in 2007, abdominal aortic stent placement in 2017, cholecystectomy, multiple organ damage. The patient was admitted to Wuhan Iron and Steel General Hospital on [16 Jan 2020] for 6 days due to intermittent cough, headache, fatigue and fever. Chest CT on [16 Jan 2020] showed bilateral pneumonia, fibrosis of the left upper lung, and nodules of the left upper lung. Dyspnea occurred on [17 Jan 2020] and blood gas analysis revealed type 1 respiratory failure. Oxygen, anti-infection, anti-virus, and sputum treatment were given. At 10:10 on [20 Jan 2020], the patient suddenly developed reduced finger pulse oxygen to 40%. He was given non-invasive ventilator-assisted ventilation. The patient was again diagnosed with severe respiratory failure and asked again whether he wanted to undergo tracheal intubation. At 10:35 on [20 Jan 2020], his condition deteriorated and resuscitation efforts failed.

6. A 75-year-old male, was admitted to Wuhan Fifth Hospital at 17:19 on [11 Jan 2020] due to fever with cough, sputum for 5 days, and vomiting for 2 days. Previous history of hypertension and hip arthroplasty. The admission temperature was 38.2 C, accompanied by fatigue, anorexia, cough, nasal congestion, dizziness, and headache. There were no obvious chills, or sore muscles and joints. A CT of the chest revealed an interstitial lung infection. After being admitted to the hospital, he was in critical condition and was given oxygen, anti-infection, anti-virus, phlegm, fever, and fluid rehydration as appropriate. The patient's condition worsened progressively, and he was transferred to the ICU on [15 Jan 2020] for mechanical ventilation. At 11:30 on [20 Jan 2020], the family members expressed their understanding of the condition and then requested to stop the ventilator and pull out the tracheal tube for observation. The tracheal intubation ventilator assisted breathing and CPR rescue were no longer indicated. He was pronounced dead at 11:25 on [20 Jan 2020].

7. A 48-year-old female, with prior history of diabetes and cerebral infarction. On [10 Dec 2019], there was no fever (38 C/100.4 F); sore body and fatigue, and cough and sputum gradually appeared. Anti-infective treatment in primary hospitals did not improve her condition over 2 weeks. On [27 Dec 2019], chest tightness and shortness of breath occurred. At Tongji Hospital she was given non-invasive ventilation and conventional anti-infective treatment. Her condition still worsened. On [31 Dec 2019], she was transferred to Jinyintan Hospital and given symptomatic treatments such as high-flow oxygen inhalation of nasal catheter. Hypoxia had not improved significantly, and her condition was still worsening. On [14 Jan 2020], chest CT showed diffuse mechanized changes in both lungs, some with traction bronchiectasis, especially in the lower lungs. At 11:50 on [20 Jan 2020], tracheal intubation was performed, and analgesia and sedation were given. The terminal oxygen saturation and blood pressure continued to decline, and then the heart rate decreased. Eventually, resuscitation efforts failed.

8. An 82-year-old male, was admitted to Wuhan Fifth Hospital at 15:41 on [14 Jan 2020] due to chills and soreness in the whole body for 5 days. He was given ECG monitoring, non-invasive ventilator assisted breathing, anti-infection, anti-virus and symptomatic treatment. On [19 Jan 2020], he had unclear speech, and his left limb was weak. Considering a stroke, the disease progressed, and respiratory failure continued to worsen. At 00:30 on [21 Jan 2020], the patient's heart rate suddenly decreased, the heart sounds were not heard, the aortic pulse disappeared, and he was resuscitated immediately. The family members still refused mechanical ventilation via intubation and continued resuscitation. The heart rate remained unrecoverable. Death was announced at 1:18.

9. A 66-year-old male, had onset of cough on [22 Dec 2019], mainly dry cough, no fever; On [31 Dec 2019], chest tightness, shortness of breath, especially after exertion, and he went to the central hospital for treatment; He was transferred to Jinyintan Hospital on [2 Jan 2020] and his imaging findings showed diffuse lung lesions with "white lung-like" changes. After admission, symptomatic treatment such as nasal high-flow oxygen was given. Refractory hypoxemia was difficult to correct. At 10:00 on [12 Jan 2020], he had tracheal intubation with ventilator assisted breathing, sedation, body temperature of 36.7 C, respiratory distress, and continued active antibacterial treatment. On the same day, the oxygenation of the patient did not improve significantly. The inspiratory oxygen concentration of the ventilator had been reduced to about 50%, and the partial pressure of arterial oxygen was 80mmHg. The patient had a long course of illness, extremely poor immune function, and risk of septic shock. At 9:50 on [21 Jan 2020], resuscitation failed.

10. An 81-year-old male, was admitted to Wuhan First Hospital on [18 Jan 2020] due to fever for 3 days. On admission, the chest CT showed infectious lesions in both lungs. Considering viral pneumonia, the patient's renal function and pulmonary infection continued to worsen. On the morning of [22 Jan 2020], consciousness gradually disappeared, and the respiratory heart rate and blood pressure continued to decline. He refused rescue measures such as chest compressions and tracheotomy. The patient stopped breathing at 10:56 on [22 Jan 2020] and clinical death was declared.

11. An 82-year-old female, with a history of Parkinson's disease for 5 years, on oral Medopa. On [3 Jan 2020], she was diagnosed with "viral pneumonia and respiratory failure" and on [6 Jan 2020] she was in the Integrated Traditional Chinese and Western Medicine Hospital of Hubei Province due to "fever, cough, chest tightness and fatigue". She was transferred to Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital on [20 Jan 2020], but her condition progressively worsened. On [22 Jan 2020], she was treated with tracheal intubation and ventilator support, but her respiratory failure did not improve. On [22 Jan 2020], she was declared dead following resuscitation efforts at 18:00.

12. A 65-year-old male, on [11 Jan 2020] was admitted to the Wuhan First Hospital due to shortness of breath accompanied by fatigue for 3 days, which increased over the 3 days. At the time of admission, the patient had difficulty breathing, chest tightness, shortness of breath, and acute illness. He was diagnosed with severe pneumonia, acute respiratory failure, and liver damage. At 19:00 on [21 Jan 2020], he developed a decrease in heart rate and blood pressure, disappearance of light reflection by both pupils, and received immediate treatment with tracheal intubation, artificial chest compressions, cardiac strengthening, and other treatments. At 19:54, the autonomic rhythm was not restored, and clinical death was declared.

13. An 80-year-old female, became ill on [11Jan 2020]. She was admitted to China Resources Wuhan Iron & Steel General Hospital on [18 Jan 2020] due to fever, cough, wheezing, and dyspnea. She was transferred to Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital on [20 Jan 2020] because of a new coronavirus positive sample. She had a history of hypertension for more than 20 years, a history of diabetes for more than 20 years, and a history of Parkinson's disease. After admission, she was in critical condition and received intensive care, anti-infection, ventilator-assisted breathing, and symptomatic supportive treatment. However, the patient's condition did not improve, with persistent hypoxemia, unconsciousness, mechanical ventilator-assisted breathing, and she was declared dead after unsuccessful resuscitation at 16:00 on [22 Jan 2020].

14. A 53-year-old male. He had been treated in a community hospital for fever in early January [2020], but it was not effective after a few days of treatment, and fever, cough, and chest tightness worsened. On [13 Jan 2020], he went to the emergency department of Tongji Hospital. CT showed bilateral lung infection and respiratory failure. He was critically ill on [18 Jan 2020] and was treated with non-invasive ventilator support. On [20 Jan 2020], he was transferred to Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital for isolation and treatment. He was admitted to hospital with anti-infective, anti-shock, ventilator-assisted respiratory support treatment, but the patient's condition did not improve. Respiratory failure continued to worsen. At 4 o'clock on [21 Jan 2020], resuscitation was unsuccessful, and clinical death was declared.

15. An 86-year-old male, was admitted to Xinhua Hospital on [9 Jan 2020] due to fatigue for one week. No fever, history of diabetic hypertension, and colon cancer 4 years post-surgery. After admission, a CT of the lungs showed multiple ground glass shadows in both lungs, obvious hypoxia, difficulty in eating, rapid breathing, and lethargy. The family refused intubation, and he received only nasal oxygen. At 17:50 on [21 Jan 2020], heartbeat and breathing stopped and clinical death was declared.

16. A 70-year-old female. On [13 Jan 2020], she was admitted to the city's No. 1 Hospital due to the continued high fever. At the time of admission, she had blurred consciousness, acute illness, weakened heart sounds, and thick breathing sounds in both lungs. Imaging results showed severe pulmonary infection, diagnosis of severe pneumonia with severe respiratory failure. Symptomatic treatment such as active anti-infection and oxygen inhalation was given, but respiratory failure was difficult to correct. The patient was pronounced dead on [21 Jan 2020] due to respiratory failure.

17. An 84-year-old male. The patient was admitted to the Fifth Hospital of the City for 3 days due to fever, cough and wheezing at 17:04 on [9 Jan 2020]. Previous history of chronic bronchitis, unstable angina pectoris, coronary stenting, hypertension, gastrointestinal bleeding, renal insufficiency, hyperlipidemia, hyperuricemia, lacunar cerebral infarction. Due to exacerbation of the illness and persistent high fever, the patient was transferred to the ICU on [18 Jan 2020] for anti-infection and symptomatic supportive treatment. At 10:16 on [22 Jan 2020], the patient stopped breathing, his heart rate gradually slowed down, and clinical death was announced at 10:52.

